# Migrating `BackgroundProcessor` to .NET 8

## Key Problem

**`Thread.Abort()` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8.** The entire cancellation strategy must change.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — roll back partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel();

        // Wait for graceful exit with a timeout
        var effectiveTimeout = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(effectiveTimeout)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Worker didn't stop in time — log warning; cannot force-kill
            Log.Warning("Worker did not stop within timeout.");
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        _workerTask?.Wait(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Critical Pitfalls

| Issue | Details |
|-------|---------|
| **`Thread.Abort()` throws at runtime** | It compiles but throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. No replacement exists—you must use cooperative cancellation. |
| **Blocking calls ignore cancellation** | If `GetNextItem()` blocks on I/O or a `Monitor.Wait`, cancellation won't interrupt it. You must convert to async APIs that accept `CancellationToken`. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort()` gone** | No equivalent needed—`OperationCanceledException` is a normal exception, not a forced abort. |
| **`volatile bool` flag is insufficient** | A flag can't unblock a thread stuck in a synchronous wait. `CancellationToken` integrates with `WaitHandle`, `SemaphoreSlim`, channels, etc. |
| **No guaranteed force-stop** | .NET 8 has no safe way to forcibly terminate a thread. Design all work to be cancellation-aware. If you need hard boundaries, run work in a **separate process**. |

## If You Can't Make Everything Async

Use `CancellationToken` with a blocking collection:

```csharp
private readonly BlockingCollection<WorkItem> _queue = new();

private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
{
    try
    {
        foreach (var item in _queue.GetConsumingEnumerable(token))
        {
            ProcessItem(item, token);
        }
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) 
    {
        RollbackCurrentTransaction();
    }
    finally
    {
        FlushBuffers();
    }
}
```

## Migration Checklist

1. Replace `volatile bool` with `CancellationTokenSource`
2. Replace `Thread` + `IsBackground` with `Task.Run`
3. Remove all `Thread.Abort()` / `ResetAbort()` calls
4. Replace `ThreadAbortException` catch with `OperationCanceledException`
5. Pass `CancellationToken` through to all blocking/async methods
6. Implement `IDisposable` to clean up the `CancellationTokenSource`
7. Convert `Stop()` to async or use `Wait(timeout)` for synchronous callers
